    <h1 id="do-great-blue-herons-migrate-the-story-of-a-partial-migrant">Do Great Blue Herons Migrate? The Story of a Partial Migrant</h1>
<p>Yes and no — the Great Blue Heron is a classic <strong>partial migrant</strong>. Populations in Florida, along the Pacific coast from Washington to Alaska, and in the Galápagos stay put year-round, while birds breeding east of the Rockies in Canada and the northern United States move south as waters freeze.<sup id="fnref:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref:2"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:2">2</a></sup> Cornell's range guidance summarizes it simply: herons "generally move away from the northern edge of their breeding range in winter, with some flying as far south as the Caribbean."<sup id="fnref:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="the-rules-of-movement">The rules of movement</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>What triggers migration</strong>: food, not temperature. Herons tolerate real cold, but they cannot hunt through ice. Once lakes, marshes, and snow-covered fields lock up, the birds leave; where open water persists, they may stay all winter even in the north.<sup id="fnref2:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Fall timing</strong>: generally mid-September to late October, later (November–December) in Alberta and Ontario.<sup id="fnref3:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Spring timing</strong>: returns run February through April, earliest in the Midwest and South; central and coastal Canadian breeders may not return until mid-May.<sup id="fnref4:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>How far</strong>: from a few hundred miles to more than <strong>3,000 miles</strong>, with some birds wintering in Guatemala, the Caribbean, or northern South America.<sup id="fnref5:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>How they travel</strong>: alone or in small groups of about 3–12 (occasionally ~100), by day and by night.<sup id="fnref6:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="harpers-marathon-what-gps-tracking-revealed">Harper's marathon: what GPS tracking revealed</h2>
<p>In 2019, Maine biologists GPS-tagged an adult female heron named "Harper" in Harpswell. After summering on Québec's Chaleur Bay, she departed on October 3 and rewrote expectations: a <strong>nonstop, 1,424-mile (2,291 km) open-ocean flight</strong> from Saint John, New Brunswick to Nocatee, Florida in <strong>38.6 hours</strong>, averaging <strong>38 mph</strong> (max 67 mph) at an average altitude of about 607 ft (max 3,103 ft). She then island-hopped the Bahamas and settled in Cuba, completing a <strong>2,488-mile</strong> journey in eight days. Accelerometer data confirmed she was flapping/flying the entire ocean crossing — not riding a ship.<sup id="fnref:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></p>
<p>Harper wasn't typical in route but her numbers fit a broader dataset: five GPS-tagged Maine herons averaged <strong>24 mph</strong> in routine flight (range 9–60 mph) and typically flew around <strong>164 ft</strong> above ground.<sup id="fnref2:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup> Tracking also explains winter loyalty: a North Carolina male called "Big Blue" nested and wintered within the same 13 square miles of Lake Norman for six consecutive years — proof that where ice-free foraging exists, migration simply isn't necessary.<sup id="fnref3:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="western-exceptionalism">Western exceptionalism</h2>
<p>West of the Rockies, even birds from the Alaska coastline generally do not migrate. Utah's Bear River Migratory Bird Refuge hosts herons all winter; some individuals there have learned to pirate or scavenge fish caught by Common Goldeneyes in tiny pockets of open water — a behavioral workaround for frozen wetlands.<sup id="fnref:5"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:5">5</a></sup> Pacific <em>fannini</em> herons in British Columbia shift seasonally between intertidal foraging and winter grassland rodent hunting rather than migrating.<sup id="fnref:6"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:6">6</a></sup></p>
<h2 id="migration-fast-facts">Migration fast facts</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Question</th>
<th>Answer</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Do all Great Blue Herons migrate?</td>
<td>No — only northern/eastern populations; it's a partial migrant<sup id="fnref7:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Longest documented nonstop flight</td>
<td>1,424 mi over open ocean, 38.6 hrs ("Harper," 2019)<sup id="fnref4:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Typical migration speed</td>
<td>Avg 38 mph on marathon legs; ~24 mph routine<sup id="fnref5:4"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:4">4</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Flock size on migration</td>
<td>Usually solo or 3–12 birds<sup id="fnref8:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Winter destinations</td>
<td>Southern U.S., Mexico, Central America, Caribbean, N. South America<sup id="fnref9:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup><sup id="fnref2:3"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:3">3</a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Year-round regions</td>
<td>Florida, Gulf &amp; Pacific coasts (incl. S. Alaska), Galápagos<sup id="fnref10:1"><a class="footnote-ref" href="#fn:1">1</a></sup></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
